05363nam a22009135i 9780520937154DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20032003cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2021696302  a97805209371547 a10.1525/97805209371542doi  a(DE-B1597)519347  a(OCoLC)990750634  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPN1993.5.G3 4aPN1993.5.G3bF55 2004 7aPER0040002bisacsh04a791.43/6572211 aFlinn, Caryl, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe New German Cinema :bMusic, History, and the Matter of Style /cCaryl Flinn. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (331 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: “Strategies Of Remembrance” -- tPart I. Historical Predecessors: Melodrama And Modernism -- t1. Mourning,Melancholia, And “New German Melodrama” -- t2. Modernism’S Aftershocks: Peer Raben’S Film Music For Fassbinder -- tPart II. Music And The Materials Of History: Alexander Kluge -- t3. Kluge’S Assault On History: Trauma, Testimony, And Difference In The Patriot -- t4. Undoing Act 5: History, Bodies, And Operatic Remains: Kluge’S The Power Of Emotion -- tPart III. Queering History Through Camp And Kitsch -- t5. Restaging History With Fantasy: Body, Camp, And Sound In The Films Of Treut, Ottinger, And Von Praunheim -- t6. Introjecting Kitsch:Werner Schroeter, Music, And Alterity -- tCoda:Working The Pieces -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen New German cinema directors like R. W. Fassbinder, Ulrike Ottinger, and Werner Schroeter explored issues of identity—national, political, personal, and sexual—music and film style played crucial roles. Most studies of the celebrated film movement, however, have sidestepped the role of music, a curious oversight given its importance to German culture and nation formation. Caryl Flinn’s study reverses this trend, identifying styles of historical remembrance in which music participates. Flinn concentrates on those styles that urge listeners to interact with difference—including that embodied in Germany’s difficult history—rather than to "master" or "get past" it. Flinn breaks new ground by considering contemporary reception frameworks of the New German Cinema, a generation after its end. She discusses transnational, cultural, and historical contexts as well as the sexual, ethnic, national, and historical diversity of audiences. Through detailed case studies, she shows how music helps filmgoers engage with a range of historical subjects and experiences. Each chapter of The New German Cinema examines a particular stylistic strategy, assessing music’s role in each. The study also examines queer strategies like kitsch and camp and explores the movement’s charged construction of human bodies on which issues of ruination, survival, memory, and pleasure are played out.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMotion picture musiczGermanyxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszGermany. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  acinema historians.  acontemporary germany.  afamous films.  afilm buffs.  afilm students.  afilm styles.  afilm textbooks.  agerman cinema.  agerman cinematic style.  agerman culture.  agerman directors.  agerman music.  agermany.  ahistorical contexts.  ahistorical review.  akitsch.  amusic styles.  amusic.  anational identity.  anew german cinema.  anonfiction.  apersonal identity.  apolitical identity.  ar w fassbinder.  asexual identity.  atransnational contexts.  aulrike ottinger.  awerner schroeter.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe G